## 1. Executive Summary

The National Information Technology Development Agency (NITDA) carries one of the most consequential mandates in Africa's digital economy: to develop, regulate, and standardize all information technology practices across Nigeria — a nation of over 220 million citizens, 36 states, and hundreds of federal agencies.

Yet the Agency's operational capacity has not scaled at the pace of its mandate. In May 2025, NITDA itself reported that **56% of government IT projects fail** to meet their objectives due to poor design, lack of interoperability, and weak oversight. The SRAP 2024-2027 sets an ambitious target of 70% national digital literacy by 2027, while the cybersecurity landscape grows more hostile by the quarter.

**This gap between mandate and execution is not a failure of intent — it is a failure of infrastructure.**

Kusmus AI proposes a **Sovereign Intelligence Partnership** with NITDA — a sovereign AI company engineering solutions for a sovereign government agency. We have already solved analogous problems in production using a foundation model that **outperforms both Google's Gemini 3.0 and OpenAI's GPT-5.1** on reasoning and task execution benchmarks. These are not theoretical capabilities — they are live, deployed systems that NITDA's leadership can verify today at **[kusmus.org](https://kusmus.org)**.

A sovereign government agency should not depend on foreign AI APIs to execute its national mandate. It should own its intelligence. This proposal outlines how.

> [!IMPORTANT]
> This proposal does not recommend replacing NITDA's workforce. It recommends **augmenting** NITDA's existing teams with sovereign AI systems — powered by a model architecture that already surpasses the world's leading proprietary models — operating entirely within NITDA's own infrastructure, owned and controlled by the Agency.

